A symbolic memorial route is being 
built through the former Warsaw Ghetto ending at the square where 
nearly 300000 Jews were loaded onto railway cars bound for the 
Treblinka Nazi death camp 
The route is to be ready in time for ceremonies April 19 marking 
the 45th anniversary of the Warsaw Ghetto uprising the official 
Polish news agency PAP reported Tuesday Several thousand people 
from Israel the United States and other countries are expected to 
attend 
The route is to be marked with 16 shiny black stones beginning 
at the monument to the heroes of the uprising in which poorly armed 
Jewish fighters died resisting the final Nazi drive to liquidate 
the ghettos 60000 remaining Jews 
One stone marker will be placed near the mound at 18 Mila Street 
built on the ruins of the bunker headquarters of Mordechai 
Anielewicz the leader of the uprising 
It will end at the socalled Umschlagplatz or Loading 
Square on Stawki Street near the former railroad ramps Between 
July 1942 and April 1943 the Nazis loaded nearly 300000 Jews onto 
boardedup cattle cars bound for the gas chambers of Treblinka 
about 60 miles northeast of Warsaw 
The Umschlagplatz currently is marked by a modest bronze plaque 
near a busy gas station but a newly constructed monument will be 
unveiled in April 
PAP said Warsaw municipal authorities had allocated about 
132000 for the project International Jewish organizations raised 
about 30000 with some of the money covering the cost of 
importing special stonecutting machines 
